All who’d rather be at the Cuevas de Marmol (Marble Caves) right now, say aye. These caves are a breathtaking, 6,000-year-old sculpture carved by the waves of Lake General Carrera of Patagonia in Southern Chile. It’s marble in its purest form, polished only by the lapping, shaping and smoothing of the lake’s waves over thousands of years.

The swirling pattern on the cave’s interior is a mirror of the azure waters of the lake, which fluctuate according to weather and season. The shallow waters are turquoise in early spring, and they create a crystalline shimmer against the caverns' swirling walls. In the summer, the water levels rise, resulting in a deep blue color that gives the cave an unearthly hue. Stunning!

Image credit: Manon van Goethem / Guaxinim / Shutterstock.com

The long-nosed horned frog (Megophrys nasuta), also known as the Bornean horned frog, is a species of frog native to the rainforests of southern Thailand, Singapore, and Borneo, measuring just a teeny 100-120mm in length.

They are light to dark brown on the dorsal surface with varying patterns and have excellent camouflage, blending in seamlessly with the forest floor to hunt for insects and snails coming within reach of its tongue.

Males loudly call at the late day hours or dusk and actively call during intense rain. They can even announce upcoming rainfall.
​
​Image credit: Vaclav Sebek / Norjipin Saidi / Shutterstock.

Notice anything? The eastern screech owl (Megascops asio) is a small owl found in the forests and woodlands of Eastern North America, from Mexico to Canada.

They have rusty or dark gray finely patterned plumage with streaking on the underparts that blend seamlessly with their forest surroundings. World hide-and-seek champion right there. Adults weigh 121–244 g and measure up to 25 cm in length. Their wingspan can vary between 46 and 61 cm.

This owl does not actually screech, despite its name. The call of the eastern screech owl is a tremolo with a whinny-like character, similar to that of a miniature horse. They also generate a 3–5 second monotone purring trill.
​
​Image credit: Christopher McDonald / Shutterstock

node.text:
Check out this rather rare celestial phenomenon! At the center of some newborn star systems, a rare and gorgeous cosmic interaction occurs known as a Herbig-Haro object. This one, HH111, was photographed by Hubble's Wide Field Camera. 

These objects only form under very specific conditions. Newly formed stars are frequently quite active, and in some cases, they release very narrow jets of rapidly moving ionized gas – gas so hot that its molecules and atoms have lost their electrons, making it highly charged. At hundreds of kilometers per second, the streams of ionized gas crash into the clouds of gas and dust that surround newly formed stars. These energetic collisions are what give rise to Herbig-Haro objects like HH111.
​
​Image credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA, B. Nisini

node.text:
For today's #UnderwaterWednesday we're taking a dive into the gaping abyss that is the Great Blue Hole: a natural and remarkably circular marine sinkhole off the coast of Belize. At over 300 meters across and over 100 meters deep, it’s believed to be one of the biggest of its kind!
​
Evidence suggests that it originally formed as a limestone cave approximately 150,000 years ago when sea levels were lower, and collapsed stalactites have been discovered in its depths, confirming that during the distant past it wasn’t submerged.
​ 
However, a layer of hydrogen sulfide gas rests at approximately 90 meters below the surface, like a toxic portal to the lifeless, oxygen-free chasm beneath, where nothing can survive. When a scientific exploration team took a submarine through the gaseous layer in 2018, the bodies of two missing divers were discovered at the bottom.
​
Despite the dangers dwelling deep beneath the surface, the clear water of Lighthouse Reef where the hole is found is home to a number of different species, from coral to turtles, and fish to reef sharks, making it a popular spot for scuba divers to explore.
​ 
Credit: Jamiesonamission/Shutterstock

node.text:
Sir Arthur C. Clarke, writer of 2001: A Space Odyssey and proud futurist, had a lot of ideas about how the future of technology would look. Despite living in a time when computers were a strange, space-age technology and the floppy disk had only just been invented, the revolutionary writer spoke confidently about social media, instant messaging, online shopping, and much more. 

Now, an interview of him speaking in 1976 about the future shows that he was incredibly accurate, and got a huge number of things correct. 

​​Hit the image post via the link in our bio to read the full story 📖

node.text:
These are Martian “blueberries” – yum. 

Martian blueberries are actually tiny stones and may hold signs of ancient water. Millions of these tiny crystals (about 2.5mm across) litter the surface of the Red Planet. Being hematite, an iron oxide compound, they are what makes its dusty surface appear red. A false-color blue image of them snapped by the Opportunity rover in 2004, however, has given them the nickname “blueberries”. A new study suggests they are actually hydrohematite, iron oxide minerals that hold microscopic traces of ancient water. If so, Mars’s blueberry fields may be juicier than we thought.

Image credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Cornell/USGS

Talk about breath-taking! Drangarnir is the shared name for two sea stacks between the islet Tindhólmur and the island Vágar in the Faroe Islands. The distinct names of Drangarnir are Stóri Drangur and Lítli Drangur, which translates to ‘large’ and ‘small’ sea stacks.

Hiking there can be a challenge, taking up to 3 hours from the nearest village, Sørvágur, but with a sight this marvelous, it’s easy to tell how this fantasy world-looking holiday destination is rising in popularity. 

Image credit: Po S / Smit / chasehunterphotos / Shutterstock

Happy #microbemonday! This little pink-bellied draconian critter is a gastrotrich, filmed here at 1000x magnification. These critters are absolutely miniscule, at just 70 microns long (For scale, 1mm = 1000 microns 🤯 ). They’re also known as hairybacks, although their name actually means ‘hairy stomach’ as they’re covered in tiny hairs, which they beat in order to swim.
​ 
Video courtesy of @jam_and_germs
